SINGAPORE DAYBOOK: ST Engineering, Bright World, Swiber Holdings

-- B y   J a n   D a h i n t e n   a n d   P h o e b e   S e d g m a n
-- 
2011-02-20T22:27:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-20/singapore-daybook-st-engineering-bright-world-swiber-holdings.html
ST Engineering Ltd.,  Asia ’s biggest
aircraft repair company, said its VT iDirect unit won a contract
from Innmarsat valued at $60 million.  MARKETS:  *The MSCI Asia Pacific Index gained 0.5 percent at Friday’s
close.
*Singapore’s Straits Times Index rose 0.1 percent at Friday’s
close.
*The  Dow Jones Industrial Average  advanced 0.6 percent at
Friday’s close.
*The Stoxx Europe 600 Index lost 0.04 percent at Friday’s close.  EQUITY MOVERS:  *Bright World Precision Machinery Ltd. (BWPM SP): The maker of
stamping machines said full-year net income increased 113
percent to 125 million yuan ($19 million) from the previous year.
*China Oilfield Technology Services Group Ltd. (COT SP): The
oil-drilling company said it expects to report a full-year loss
due to lower sales.
*Hengxin Technology Ltd. (HENG SP): The supplier of coaxial
cables used in mobile communications said net income increased
to 102.5 million yuan from a year earlier.
*Oceanus Group Ltd. (OCNUS SP): The world’s largest operator of
abalone farms said it expects net profit for the year ended Dec.
31 will decline from the previous year.
*Singapore Land Ltd. (SL SP): One of the city’s biggest office
landlords said its full-year net income was S$661 million
($518million), compared with a loss of S$266 million a year ago.
  Singapore  Technologies Engineering Ltd. (STE SP): Asia’s
biggest aircraft repair company said its VT iDirect unit won a
contract from Inmarsat valued at $60 million.
*Swiber Holdings Ltd. (SWIB SP): The offshore logistic services
provider said it will sell its 49 percent stake in CSOTL
Offshore Co. Ltd. for $19.2 million to LS Finans AS.  SINGAPORE BUDGET:  *Singapore will spend S$6.6 billion on benefits including tax
cuts and rebates as it strives to ease the burden of inflation
ahead of elections due in the next year. The government will
hand cash to all adult citizens as a “dividend” from record
growth, boost employer pension payments, upgrade homes and
invest in improving productivity, Finance Minister Tharman
Shanmugaratnam said on Friday. The surplus will be about S$100
million in the year starting April 1, from a projected shortfall
of approximately S$300 million for the current period, he said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
